I've got a Weatherby mk. V in excellent condition (based on the NRA condition standards), the only flaws are a few little chips on the stock and a tiny fleck of rust near the end of the muzzle.  The chips on the stock are only cosmetic in nature, it's a synthetic stock so no real damage is done.  The gun is incredibly solid and shoots amazingly.  It still has a very positive edge on the extractor and ejects very easily.  It has a ported barrel to assist with recoil control.  Less than 50 rounds have been put through it and the bore is nice and bright with sharp lands and grooves.  The trigger pull is crisp, like breaking glass, and the bolt has a weighty heft to it.  It comes with a padded hard-shell case, 14 rounds of .300 Weatherby Magnum ammunition, and an approximately $600 Nikon brand scope.  I do not recall the magnification on the scope and I wasn't able to get a good picture of the bore due to only having a cellular phone camera, but it's in excellent shape.  I'm asking $1,800.00 for it.  It was over $2,000.00 when it was purchased (including the scope).

This would make a fantastic hunting or target rifle as it is very accurate and very well made.  The only reason I'm parting with it is because I'm in desperate need of money and I know it's worth what I'm asking.

Please feel free to ask any questions if you interested in buying, but make sure to read my post before you do.  If you decide you'd like to purchase it, please contact me by email and we can work out an appropriate time and place to meet.

title: For Sale:  AUG STEYR
postcontent:
I HAVE NO MAGAZINE!!!

ONLY BEEN SHOT A COUPLE OF TIMES!! 

CALL JIM AT REDACTED



At first glance, the Steyr AUG (also known as StG77) looks odd for a number of reasons. The magazine is behind the trigger, making it bullpup, there is a vertical hand grip up front and there is a standard 1.5x zoom scope. It may seem like this weapon is something out of a sience fiction movie, but infact this weapon has been in service since its creation in 1977. This weapon was designed to be a break out of the normal assault rifle. The main purpose of this was to make this weapon bullpup. For example: If there was 2 rifles, 1 bullpup and 1 traditional with both the same barrel lengths, the bullpup would be shorter but would still have the same accuracy as the traditional rifle because the barrel goes down further into the gun. This gives the user a shorter profile and because of this, many special forces around the world use it. The Steyr AUG A1 comes with a non removable 1.5x scope which is very useful for longer ranges. The front hand grip aids in better handling for longer ranges, so with this weapon the user is capable of great accuracy with it. Another useful feature of the AUG is interchangable barrels. If there is a firefight thats taking place at long range and a user has a Steyr AUG with too short of a barrel, the user can rather quickly get out a longer barrel and put it on. The Steyr AUG uses 5.56x45mm ammunition or for the submachine gun variant, the 9mm round. The Steyr AUG can accept 30 or 42 round box magazines and a nice feature of some magazines is that they are clear plastic so the user can see how many rounds they have left.

postcontent:
For sale/trade is a Belgian Parlor Pistol from the 1800's. It has been looked at by a proffesional and he has confirmed that it is most likely Belgian. There are no markings except 2 notches carved on the under side of the barrel. The very tip of the hammer was broken off a long time ago. Send me an offer! Willing to ship.

 Parlor pistols and rifles (zimmerschutzen from German, "room marksman" or "room shoot") were popularized in the mid to late 19th Century, particularly in the Germanic countries, as a way to entertain guests, have family fun, and to increase one's shooting skills. Generally heavy barreled and often elaborately engraved rifles (zimmerbusche) were produced for clearly upscale clients. These generally used a Flobert (CB-Cap) cartridge chambered a few inches from the muzzle. Sometimes equally elaborate parlor pistols (zimmerpistole) were chambered for Flobert cartridges or simply used a percussion cap. In this country, a small, almost toylike parlor pistol was briefly manufactured by Remington in 1860.

title: For Sale:  Norinco SKS, case, bayo, sling, bipod, strippers
postcontent:
Up for sale is a nice Chinese SKS.   Uses the 7.62 x 39 cartridge that's good for plinking, hunting, targets, you name it; and the round is still very affordable so shooting this rifle is easy on the wallet.  This hasn't been shot much (I've got waaay too many rifles for each of them to get fully 'exercised'...lol.  And another project on the horizon necessitates this going up for sale.)

Comes with an upgraded ATI Monte Carlo stock for improved ergonomics.  Also has an add on muzzle brake (you can remove it with a hex key if you like) to reduce muzzle flare and recoil. 

Receiver was originally drilled/tapped on the left side for a scope mount when this rifle was imported.  No longer has the mount BUT the mounting holes are still there and there are hex head machine screws in place; if you want to add a firm/hold the zero mount to this rifle the hard part has been done!

 Has a five round detachable magazine installed (great for hunting when you've got a limit on how many rounds  your weapon can hold AND a 30 round metal detachable magazine as well.  

Bayo, with mounting screw and all hardware is included.  Bipod is included that can be installed/uninstalled in about three minutes depending on your preference.

Nice leather sling and three stripper clips to get you going are also part of the package.  Hard sided case to contain everything rounds out the offering.

Matching number on the trigger group, bolt carrier, and bolt; this isn't a "parts gun" that's been put together piecemeal.

IF you can find an SKS, you then have to find a nice one.  This is it!  Prices have escalated steadily but rather than play games of "start high/negotiate like crazy", I've got this priced at $395 cash, and that's both a fair AND a firm price.  First "I'll take it" at the listed price gets first shot.  I have more photos than Armslist allows to be posted, let me know if you want more and we'll go from there.  I'm around most of the weekend, with the exception of a graduation Saturday morning.  

I'd be happy to drive a bit to meet you if that helps, let's say as far north as Lomira, as far west as Johnson Creek, and to Hwy 20 in the Racine area as the "circle of travel".

You have to be old enough to purchase a rifle, have picture ID, and be willing to sign a bill of sale.  Thanks for looking.
